===Etymology===
Widely assumed to be from {{compound|grape|fruit|lang=en}}, an allusion to the supposed grapelike clusters of fruit on the tree, early {{C.|19}} Ciardi proposes another theory: one of the pummelo's botanical names is {{taxlink|Citrus grandis|species|noshow=1|ver=161111}}, meaning "great citrus [fruit]", due to the size of its fruit. A new pummelo variety might first have been called a "greatfruit", and through the process of [[w:Assimilation (phonology)|assimilation]], the word came to be pronounced "grapefruit".

